5da58f0b4664"],

Cell["\<\
The ' > and \"> prompts occur during string collection (another way of saying \
that MySQL is waiting for completion of a string). \
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.779342841828599*^9, 3.779342847970151*^9}, 
   3.813394515844495*^9, {3.813433075392181*^9, 3.813433075392538*^9}, 
   3.8134409018750887`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"2dbed8d4-9161-4bab-b49f-\
a72ea344e531"],

Cell["\<\
In MySQL, you can write strings surrounded by either ' or \" characters (for \
example, ' hello' or \"goodbye\"), and mysql lets you enter strings that span \
multiple lines. \
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.779342841828599*^9, 3.779342847970151*^9}, 
   3.813394515844495*^9, {3.813433087853232*^9, 
   3.813433087855898*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"88f13174-ec18-4504-ae00-\
12453bb6d77c"],

Cell["\<\
When you see a ' > or \"> prompt, it means that you have entered a line \
containing a string that begins with a ' or \" quote character, but have not \
yet entered the matching quote that terminates the string.\
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.779342841828599*^9, 3.779342847970151*^9}, 
   3.813394515844495*^9, 
   3.813440906131942*^9},ExpressionUUID->"6cb72be0-143c-4061-8a42-\
5f7eb7d8133d"],

Cell["\<\
Notice that you do not have my_table in your system, the following is just an \
illustration for the syntax of querying. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.813395849950474*^9, 3.8133958849287243`*^9}, {
  3.8134331061475987`*^9, 
  3.81343310959548*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"def9f0ce-5a5c-4f44-9dae-\
b702b5380191"],

